article.description: Lindsay Whalen scored 30 points to lead No. 9 Minnesota past stubborn Creighton 82-71 Thursday night, proving the Gophers can handle a determined opponent.
article.headline: Whalen scores 30 on scrappy Bluejays
article.linkText: No. 7 Gophers win, give Borton 100th win
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Pam Borton's 100th coaching win was more than
just a milestone victory.

Lindsay Whalen scored 30 points to lead No. 7 Minnesota past
stubborn Creighton 82-71 Thursday night, proving the Gophers can
handle a determined opponent.

"It's great for us to play against a team like this," said
Borton, who returned 12 players from a team that won 24 games last
season. "That's what we need to get us ready for the Big 10 and
NCAA tournament. We held our composure."

Six games into her second season at Minnesota, Borton has led
the Gophers to 31 wins, after piling up 69 victories in four
seasons at Vermont.

"I'm more concerned about how our team does than how many wins
I have," Borton said.

Janel McCarville had 21 points and 10 rebounds for Minnesota
(6-0), which tied a school record with its 14th straight home win.
The Bluejays (2-3) got 20 points from Christy Neneman and stayed
close well into the second half.

"I was a little disappointed in the first half, how their
full-court pressure kind of affected us and took us out of our
game," said Whalen, who tied a school record by making all 14 of
her free-throw attempts. "We really didn't run our system. I made
a point to be more aggressive."

The Gophers were up by 11 points early before Creighton used a
full-court press to get back in the game. The Bluejays closed the
first half with a 26-6 run, and Neneman's layup six minutes into
the second half tied the game at 50.

Minnesota then went on a 9-0 run, capped by a basket from Liz
Podominick off a nifty feed from McCarville for a 59-50 lead. The
Bluejays climbed to within 59-55 on Laura Spanheimer's 3-pointer,
but couldn't get any closer.

"The difference between the first and second half is we didn't
quite consciously make the effort in transition," Creighton coach
Jim Flanery said.

Kelly Roysland's jumper and two free throws by Whalen capped a
13-2 run to put the Gophers ahead 70-57 with 6:11 remaining. Whalen
made all 14 of her free-throw attempts, tying a school record, and
added seven assists.

Angie Janis scored 15 and Dayna Finch added 14 for Creighton,
who threw a scare into a ranked team for the second time this
season. The Bluejays lost to No. 25 Auburn 79-72 on Nov. 29.

Roysland added 10 points for the Gophers.
